    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-24T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-24T16:00:00-05:00" n="474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.00 Revolutions/86: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gonzalez</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-24T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 24, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 25—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>62. Referring to my telegram No. 61, October 23, 9 a.m., <hi rend="italic">coup
                        d’état</hi> consummated without any apparent opposition. Three army officers
                    have been appointed to the Cabinet including the previous Minister of Finance
                    who is acting as Foreign Minister. In view of the announced intention to remove
                    corrupt elements which was the ostensible reason for the movement, many changes
                    in Government officers are expected.</p>
                <p>Inasmuch as constitutional succession was disregarded the question of recognition
                    arises upon which I shall report fully.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gonzalez</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
